<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-486-784  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 486 784.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  April 25 1990 n131 p24(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business andamp; Computer Publications(England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>UK PC market grows despite grim forecasts.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MicrocomputersComputer IndustryUnited KingdomMarket AnalysisGrowth.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>UK PC market grows despite grim forecasts Despite poor forecasts, the UKbusiness PC market grew by 29.4 per cent in terms of unit sales in 1989.andP;  IBMand Compaq registered the strongest growth, according to an annual review bymarket research company, Romtec.andM;&quot;A bigger slip back was expected on the 31 per cent unit sales figure set for1988,&quot; commented an industry analyst at Romtec.andP;  &quot;But a very strong fourthquarter, bolstered by the SX chip which represents a real volume market,pushed it up.&quot;andM;IBM's PC unit sales alone grew by 50.9 per cent in 1989, shored up by itsModel 55 386SX and Model 70 386DX products.andP;  This also helped increase theMCA share of the market from 13.3 per cent in 1988 to 19.5 per cent in 1989.andM;Compaq, whose SLT portable was the year's highest selling portable, overtookAmstrad to take number two spot in the PC business vendor stakes.andP;  &quot;Amstrad'sunit share fell from 17.1 per cent to 11.3 per cent in 1989 as its 286 and386 products failed to take off,&quot; said Romtec's analyst.andM;IBM overtook Compaq in the 386 market during 1989.andP;  Toshiba, with itsportables and transportables, also chalked up a notable growth from 3.7 percent to 5.1 per cent.andM;* NCR profits for the first quarter of this year took a 15 per cent dive,despite a substantial gain in orders.andP;  The company blamed lower profitmargins on sales in the the US and Europe.andP;  NCR's agressive share re-purchasealso contributed to the fall.andO;</TEXT></DOC>